               <msContents>
                  <summary>This complete copy of the <title>Taẕkirat al-Shuʻarā</title> (Chronicles
                     of Poets) by Dawlatshāh Samarqandī (d. ca. 1494) contains biographical accounts
                     of some 150 poets, together with selections of their poems. The author, from a
                     ruling Timurid-era elite family, dedicated this work to the cultural and
                     political figure <persName role="dte" ref="https://viaf.org/viaf/22198747/"
                        key="person_22198747">Mīr ‘Alī Shīr Navā'ī (d. 1501)</persName>. A scribe
                     named <persName xml:lang="ar-Latn-x-lc" type="supplied" key="person_f2475"
                        role="scr" change="#role-assignment">Muḥammad Amān</persName> copied this
                     manuscript, apparently in India, for a patron named <persName role="pat"
                        key="person_f6880">Shaykh Niẓām al-Dīn Aḥmad Bilgrāmī ‘Uthmānī</persName> in
                        <date calendar="#Hijri-qamari" when="1749">13 Rajab 1162 AH (29 June 1749
                        CE)</date>.</summary>
                  <msItem xml:id="Persian_MS_54-item1">
                     <author ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/79263034" key="person_79263034"
                        change="#ids-cleanup">
                        <persName xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" type="standard">Dawlatshāh Samarqandī, d.
                           ca. 1494</persName>
                        <persName xml:lang="fa">دولتشاه سمرقندى</persName>
                     </author>
                     <editor role="scr"><persName xml:lang="ar-Latn-x-lc" type="supplied"
                           key="person_f2475" role="scr" change="#role-assignment">Muḥammad
                           Amān</persName></editor>
                     <editor role="pat"><persName key="person_f6880">Shaykh Niẓām al-Dīn Aḥmad
                           Bilgrāmī ‘Uthmānī</persName></editor>
                     <title xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" key="work_20871" change="#ids-cleanup"
                        >Taz̲kirah-i Dawlatshāh</title>
                     <title xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" type="alt" key="work_20871"
                        change="#ids-cleanup">Taz̲kirat al-Shuʻarā</title>
                     <title xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" key="work_20871" change="#ids-cleanup">تذکرة
                        دولتشاه</title>
                     <title xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" type="alt" key="work_20871"
                        change="#ids-cleanup">تذکرة الشعراء</title>
                     <incipit xml:lang="fa"><locus from="1b" to="1b"> برگ ۱پ (folio 1b):</locus>
                        تحمیدی که شاهباز بلند پرواز اندیشه بساخت فضای آن پرواز نتواند نمود. </incipit>
                     <explicit xml:lang="fa"><locus from="182a" to="182a"> برگ ۱۸۲ر (folio
                           182ab):</locus> مگر صاحبدلی روزی برحمت کند بر حال این مسکین
                        دعایی.</explicit>
                     <colophon xml:lang="fa">
                        <locus from="182a" to="182a"> برگ ۱۸۲ر (folio 182ab):</locus> .الحمد لله
                        والمنیبه که این کتاب مستطاب تذکره الشعرا من تالیف دولتشاه علا والد د له بختی
                        شاه رحمتهما الله تعالی داد بتاریخ سیزده ۱۳ رجب المرجب فی سنه ۱۱۶۲ اثنی و
                        ستین و مایه و الف من هجرت محمد مصطفی صلی الله علیه و اله و اصحابه و سلم
                        مطابق سنه ۲ جلوس احمد شاه بادشاه غازی خلد الله ملکه و سلطنت حسب خواستن شیخ
                        نظام الدین احمد بلگرامی عثمانی بید اضعاف العباد محمد اما صورت اختتام یافت </colophon>
                     <colophon xml:lang="en"> Completed by <persName xml:lang="ar-Latn-x-lc"
                           type="supplied" key="person_f2475" role="scr" change="#role-assignment"
                           >Muḥammad Amān</persName> on <date calendar="#Hijri-qamari" when="1749"
                           >13 Rajab 1162 AH (29 June 1749 CE)</date>, in the second year of the
                        reign of the Mughal ruler Emperor Aḥmad Shāh Bahādur, for <persName
                           role="pat" key="person_f6880">Shaykh Niẓām al-Dīn Aḥmad Bilgrāmī
                           ‘Uthmānī</persName>. </colophon>
                     <textLang mainLang="fa">Persian</textLang>
                     <note>Probably one of the four copies formerly owned by <persName cert="medium"
                           role="fmo ins" key="person_44733962"
                           ref="https://viaf.org/viaf/44733962/">Sir Gore Ouseley</persName>, who
                        repeatedly refers to it in his essay on Persian poets, as does former owner
                           <persName type="standard" role="ins fmo"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/20108923/" key="person_20108923">Nathaniel
                           Bland</persName> in his seminal essay on chronicles of poets. For other
                        copies in the Rylands collections, see <ref
                           target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_6801"><idno>Persian
                              MS 309</idno></ref>, <ref
                           target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_6803">310</ref>,
                        and <ref target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_7346"
                           >838</ref>.</note>
                  </msItem>
               </msContents>
               <physDesc>
                  <objectDesc form="codex">
                     <supportDesc material="chart">
                        <support>Text block comprised of medium-weight, cross-grained,
                           cream-coloured paper probably manufactured in the <placeName cert="high"
                              ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7000208">Indian
                              subcontinent</placeName>.</support>
                        <extent><measure>182 folios, 10 flyleaves (ff. iv + 182 + vi)</measure>.
                              <dimensions type="leaf" unit="mm">
                              <height>235</height>
                              <width>160</width>
                           </dimensions>
                           <dimensions type="written" unit="mm">
                              <height>190</height>
                              <width>120</width>
                           </dimensions>
                        </extent>
                        <foliation xml:id="original">
                           <p>Foliation marked at top-left of the a sides in Hindu-Arabic numerals
                              starting on folio 9.</p>
                        </foliation>
                        <collation>Undetermined. <catchwords>Catchwords irregularly
                              marked.</catchwords></collation>
                        <condition>Handle with caution. Insect damage at the beginning and final 20
                           pages remain unrepaired. </condition>
                     </supportDesc>
                     <layoutDesc>
                        <layout columns="1" writtenLines="17"> Written in 1 column with 17 lines per
                           page. Ruled with a <hi rend="italic">misṭarah</hi> hand guide.</layout>
                     </layoutDesc>
                  </objectDesc>
                  <handDesc>
                     <handNote scope="major" script="nasta_liq" medium="ink">
                        <desc>Copied by <persName xml:lang="ar-Latn-x-lc" type="supplied"
                              key="person_f2475">Muḥammad Amān</persName> in neat nasta'liq script
                           with occasional shikastah ligatures in <material>black</material> with
                           headers and verse markers in <material>red</material>.</desc>
                     </handNote>
                  </handDesc>
                  <additions>
                     <lb/>
                     <label>Marginalia</label>
                     <list>
                        <item>Glosses, comments and emendations in Persian throughout. </item>
                        <item>Pencilled notations in English, probably in the hand of former owner
                              <persName type="standard" role="ins fmo"
                              ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/20108923/" key="person_20108923">Nathaniel
                              Bland</persName>.</item>
                     </list>
                     <label>Inscriptions:</label>
                     <list>
                        <item> Folio <locus from="1a" to="1a">1a</locus> bears a note in English,
                           probably in the hand of <persName cert="medium" role="fmo ins"
                              key="person_44733962" ref="https://viaf.org/viaf/44733962/">Sir Gore
                              Ouseley</persName>: <q xml:lang="en">No 28. ‘Memoirs of the Poets’ by
                              Doulat Shah Samarkandi transcribed by Muhammed Aman AH 1162 – A.D.
                              1749.</q>
                        </item>
                        <item>Folio <locus from="1b" to="1b">1b</locus>, top bears a caricatured
                           image of a sea monster in black ink, that someone evidently sketched to
                           obscure an earlier inscription, probably the signature of a former
                           owner.</item>
                     </list>
                     <label>Bookplates:</label>
                     <list>
                        <item>
                           <locus from="xa" to="xa">Final flyleaf a side</locus>: <q xml:lang="en"
                              >Bland MSS No. 64</q>. </item>
                        <item>
                           <locus from="xb" to="xb">Final flyleaf b side</locus>: <q xml:lang="en"
                              >Bibliotheca Lindesiana</q> with shelf mark <q xml:lang="en">2/F</q>.
                        </item>
                     </list>
                  </additions>
                  <bindingDesc>
                     <binding notBefore="1749" notAfter="1800">
                        <p>Bound with ornate, painted lacquer <material>pasteboard</material> covers
                           that appear contemporary with the manuscript, then apparently later
                           restored for former owner <persName cert="medium" role="fmo ins"
                              key="person_44733962" ref="https://viaf.org/viaf/44733962/">Sir Gore
                              Ouseley</persName>. Resewn on three sunken cords, with flyleaves of
                           European heavy-weight, flocked, gray-coloured paper, ivory-coloured
                           added. Edges trimmed and spattered in fine blue, with European-style
                           front-bead decorative endbands sewn over a flat core. The binder laced
                           the cords into the original boards, then rebacked the <locus from="Spine"
                              to="Spine">spine</locus> in calf <material>leather</material>,
                           hollow-backed, with internal calfskin <material>leather</material> hinges
                           put down upon the flyleaves to reconnect the textblock.</p>
                        <decoNote type="binding"><p>Board exteriors painted with elaborate floral
                              bouquets on grounds that contains iridescent, finely ground
                                 <material>mica</material> or <material>nacre</material> particles.
                              The internal doublures feature a central narcissuses, with floral
                              garlands underneath, and butterflies on either side, painted on red
                              grounds. The rebacked <locus from="Spine" to="Spine">spine</locus>
                              tooled with a foliate decorative roll on the exterior in
                                 <material>gold</material>, with a floriate decorative roll in blind
                              on the interior hinges.</p></decoNote>
                        <p><dimensions type="binding" unit="mm">
                              <height>254</height>
                              <width>173</width>
                              <depth>33</depth>
                           </dimensions></p>
                        <condition>Handle binding with caution. Lacquer delaminating along the outer
                           edges of the boards, with the corners exposed. Boxed.</condition>
                     </binding>
                  </bindingDesc>
               </physDesc>
               <history>
